A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily confers full powers on it, he decided to play the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial disruptions.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "treasoning his word" and "strengthening the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a step to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be organized within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to give up their draft to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to recover a popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview to the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote on my text or hold full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, a vast majority of Islamist, voted the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not enforce their views.
Human rights representatives, religious minorities and civil society did likewise.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 persons, substitute members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As was expected, the voting papers were unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed virtually at the time of prayer, so that several members of the committee came to think that the timepiece of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of the law, remains the same as that of the Constitution of 1971."
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The Liberals think it is a hypocrisy and they think it is nothing more than an advertising act.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is made through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who must confirm his conformity with Sharia laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not scholars but university students, some of whom are trained in the French system," explains Alexis Bluet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity about article 220, for the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might be raised in the future would be to what extent are the competent civil judges to pronounce themselves above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers entrusted to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will argue that there are few compared to those during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
As the military wishes, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Civil prosecutions will not be prohibited in military courts, as requested by human rights associations.
These also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider to be libertified.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and now insults are banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially in the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, reports Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
