- Of course you can't be considered a panacea, you're still waiting to resolve the issue of privacy, because you don't always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of computer interaction are good, but each one in his own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not in loose movements, but shorter.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of the bones and muscles.
For now it is very big, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How is that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this soda can?
You'll talk and show it at the same time.
- Usually I'm just talking.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- I mean, do you want to force users to adapt to what they can or cannot do right now?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I believe that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Are you missing resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with the three-dimensional recognition.
