In the film the moods are combined. On the one hand we find well documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits, emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were shown in the same way in the film, do not differ much in this respect.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes are somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes from the CIA's central and other institutions: brought men who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the office halls, by telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectful director and his way of doing things has ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is its third feature film, after "Friendly Small, Adieux" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film in which action has no place in the city of Boston, where it grew up.
The sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was also a characteristic that placed old film directors above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran is "flyed" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic capacity that at the same time conveys the excitement of the confusion and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the imposter team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
