For this, you have to go down every day to the bottom of your crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the insides of the Earth is solidified by getting in touch with the air.
After tearing out large sulphur rocks, which total about 70 pounds [70 kg], they carry them in two bamboo baskets that carry on their shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb through the turtle, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps not to slip and fall by the precipice.
